data.content:
In xUnit:

- **Per-test setup/teardown** (`[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`) → **constructor** / `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **One-time setup/teardown** (`[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`) → a **class fixture** implementing `IDisposable`, injected via `IClassFixture<T>`

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
// Replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Replaces [TestFixture]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact] // Replaces [Test]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name); // note: expected comes first in xUnit
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**
- xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/`Dispose` naturally replace `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`.
- `IClassFixture<T>` shares one fixture instance across all tests in the class — matching `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]` semantics.
- If you need to share across multiple classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` instead.
